posts.name: David Loh
posts.cooked: This thread was useful for addressing loop overruns, especially concerning thread priority adjustments, though caution is needed as altering thread priority may lead to unintended consequences when code execution remains slow. The team encountered a loop overrun exceeding one second during auto initialization. The sole action being executed is pathplanner buildAuto. The team is seeking advice on whether any inefficiency exists in their implementation. Additionally, they are considering whether warming up the auto builder beforehand, such as by invoking getAutonomousCommand prior to the auto initialization process. For further details, please refer to the GitHub repository located at https://github.com/FIRST-Team-1699/robocats2025.

posts.name: Elliot Scher
posts.cooked:
We encountered an issue where the system isn't functioning correctly. Specifically, the cached trajectories are being loaded too early, causing problems during execution. After implementing the suggested fix, we've observed that the cached data now behaves appropriately. However, the overall performance hasn't met our expectations due to inefficiencies in how resources are managed.

In the current implementation:
- The `loadAutoTrajectories` method initializes all required cached trajectories upfront
- Each trajectory is assigned to variables for later use
- The code structure includes multiple trajectory commands followed by corresponding variable assignments
- The final set of cached commands is incomplete

posts.name: Krish Parmar
posts.cooked: After analyzing your code, I believe your issue stems from the auto-chooser component. It accepts a runnable object but does not execute the command immediately when added to the auto-chooser—it instead schedules it for execution later. This could lead to unexpected behavior, such as a loop-overrun due to excessive initial loading requirements. However, I am not entirely certain about this reasoning.

posts.name: David Loh
posts.cooked:
I don’t think the issue is with the autochooser. The autochooser loads all paths in the RobotContainer constructor, so it’s unlikely causing loop overruns on enable.

I know you were uncertain about raising thread priority, but if you have enough time to test before your next competition, I suggest trying it. We implemented it during a full competition, and it significantly reduced our loop overruns. However, if your cycle times remain around 20 ms or you notice signs of thread starvation, like stale CAN frames or odometry that doesn’t update, consider switching back.

posts.name: Todd
posts.cooked:
It’s weird that so much time is unaccounted for by Tracer

The ‘UserCodeMS’ timer in advantagekit’s overridden main loop seems pretty concrete

While it’s worst at the start of autonomous there are recurring long loops through the rest of autonomous and even into teleop none of which Tracer is able to identify any substantive delay in which makes me a little suspicious of your assumption that the paths are being regenerated plus your code seems to be fine

By adding a print it’s easy to verify that the commands generated in your AutonomousCommands.java function are called during disabled as long as its selected in the dashboard

The only thread I see is that while it seems to be uncaught by Tracer’s diagnostics each one of the spikes does seem to correlate to an overrun that – is – caught by tracer just on wildly different magnitudes (20-40ms overruns from what I’ve seen)

The Advantagekit timing in ‘Logger’ pretty solidly accounts for the extra things advantage kit sneaks in between cycles and none of them have a substantive magnitude (at least not substantive enough to correlate with the ~150ms overruns you’re seeing in FullCycleMS

Pretty confusing I wish I had something to recommend trying I suppose I’d start with trying to turn Logger off during autonomous and see if Tracer still fires off
